Abstract

Summary of analysis.

Research question

Brief description of the “research question” you are exploring, possibly including your hypothesis.

In this study different cell morphology parameters were studied how they describe cell growth and differentiation. In this study cell area and cell perimeter was analysed and also goal was also to find parmater describing cell branchiness.

Hypothesis is that cell area increases with cell age / time, cell perimeter increases with cell age / time, cell branchiness increases with cell age / time.

Data wrangling part

Link to data wrangling script https://github.com/sofiaoja/IODS-final.

Description of data and its variables

Description of your data and its variables. Where is the data from, what does it relate to, what do the variables represent, what has been done to the data before analysis?

Cells were measured at imaging lab and analysed with machine vision analysis software and various cell morphology parameters were obtained.

Cell morphology parameters

  • ObjectAreaCh1 = area of the cell
  • ObjectPerimCh1 = perimeter of the cell
  • ObjectShapeP2ACh1
  • ObjectShapeLWRCh1
  • ObjectShapeBFRCh1
  • ObjectLengthCh1
  • ObjectWidthCh1
  • ObjectConvexHullAreaRatioCh1
  • ObjectConvexHullPerimRatioCh1

Visually clear and interesting explorations of the variables of interest in the data, from the point of view of your research question. Include interpretations of the distributions and relationships of the variables. Use captions to draw the reader’s focus on the interesting parts of your tables and graphics.

# regression model with multiple explanatory variables
my_model_p1_006 <- lm(p1_006$ObjectAreaCh1 ~ p1_006$ObjectPerimCh1 + p1_006$ObjectLengthCh1 + p1_006$ObjectWidthCh1, data = p1_006)

# print out a summary of the model
# The relationship between the chosen explanatory variables and the target 
# variable is statistically significant for variable p1_006$ObjectLengthCh1 and p1_006$ObjectWidthCh1 ('***' 0.001), and 
# for p1_006$ObjectPerimCh1 ('*' 0.05). Multiple R squared of the model is 0.8307, which is 
# quite high thus linear model might explain this data. (Ref Wikipedia: In statistics, the coefficient of multiple correlation is a measure of how well a given variable can be predicted using a linear function of a set of other variables).
summary(my_model_p1_006)

# principal component analysis (PCA) for standardized data

# clean columns

# standardize the variables
p1_006_std <- scale(p1_006)

# perform principal component analysis (with the SVD method)
